ch pointing to the agent's file content on the assumption that the user will commit the remaining agent changes in a future commit. But the session is ended and those changes were intentionally discarded.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Failure 3: TestTrailerRemovalSkipsCondensation\\n\\n**What the test does:**\\n1. Agent creates `trailer_test.go`\\n2. User commits with `git -c core.hooksPath=/dev/null commit -m \\\"Add trailer_test (no checkpoint)\\\"` -- explicitly bypassing all git hooks\\n3. Test expects: no checkpoint trailer, no condensation, and no shadow branches\\n\\n**What actually happened (from entire.log):**\\n- Session starts, agent creates `trailer_test.go`, checkpoint saved on shadow branch `entire/1ec27f0-e3b0c4`\\n- Session ends (phase: idle -> ended)\\n- The commit uses `core.hooksPath=/dev/null`, so **no git hooks fire at all** -- no prepare-commit-msg, no commit-msg, no post-commit\\n- The shadow branch `entire/1ec27f0-e3b0c4` is never cleaned up because the cleanup logic lives entirely in the `PostCommit` hook handler\\n\\n**Root cause:** This is an **expected limitation**, not a bug in the CLI per se. When the user bypasses git hooks, the CLI has no opportunity to clean up. However, the test's name suggests it's testing \\\"trailer removal\\\" behavior, but the implementation bypasses hooks entirely rather than removing a trailer. The test assertion that shadow branches should be gone is **unreasonable** given that all cleanup mechanisms were bypassed.\\n\\n**However**, from a user perspective, this scenario does represent a real case: a user might commit without hooks (e.g., `--no-verify`, or manually setting `core.hooksPath`). The shadow branch would linger forever unless the user runs `entire cleanup` or a new session starts and orphan detection kicks in. This is the same fundamental issue as Failure 1 -- there's no mechanism to clean up shadow branches outside of the post-commit hook path that requires a checkpoint trailer.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary Tabl